Exercise

In this exercise we will obtain a cubic approximation of \(\displaystyle{@bb@}\).

  1. First we write the expression \(\displaystyle{@bb@}\) in a form suitable for the binomial series, \(a(1+y)^p\) for some constant \(a\) and some \(y\) which depends on \(x\).
    \(\displaystyle{@bb@}=\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]

  2. Now use the binomial series to approximate \(\displaystyle{@bb@}\) by a cubic polynomial.
    \(\displaystyle{@bb@}\approx\) [[input:ans2]][[validation:ans2]] [[feedback:prt2]]

generalfeedback.text:
1.       \({\displaystyle{@bb@}=\frac{1}{{@aa@}}\left(1+\frac{x}{{@aa@}}\right)^{-1}}\)

  2. \(\displaystyle{@bb@}\approx{@ta1@}\)

Below illustrates the close correspondence (when \(x\) is ‘small’) between the curves \(y=\frac{1}{2}(1 +x^2)^{−1}\) and \(y=\frac{1}{2}−\frac{x} {4}+\frac{x^2}{8}−\frac{x^3}{16}\).
